A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions

node.text:
My friend Karta Healy pops up pretty much every year on the Côte d’Azur, and (as far as I know) always gives me a shout. Last time was in December for Cars & Coffee Monaco, where he showed up with an improbable wagon Citroën DS.

That was the last time, until a couple of weeks ago when he sent me a message asking me the name of my friends’ hotel-restaurant at the top of Col de Turini with all the memorabilia of Rallye Monte-Carlo.

He’d be finishing a trip through the Alps, from Stuttgart to Cap d’Antibes and wanted to meet me there for lunch in late July, and he sent me info about the trip. It looked cool but when we finally met it was much more than that.

Karta and his dad Cameron had just been driving a Porsche 964 prepared for off-roading from Stuttgart through Black Forest, Val d’Isère, Chamonix, Sauze d’Oulx, Serre Chevalier and Jausiers, through little roads, if not off-road. Alongside were three other 964s and two 993, all extra light and prepared with off-road tyres, rear roll cage, underbody protection, roof rack and lifted rally shock absorbers.

We spent time to enjoy lunch together and we all go down to Monaco where the six 911s will enjoy a lap or the F1 track alongside more Porsche - two Cayennes tailored by the @jankalmarbeyondadventure crew. It was their first trip of this kind and I’m already waiting for a call for the next one…

Photos & words @romuald_clariond for @type7

node.text:
“Nostalgia, romanticism, escapism, these are the ingredients of my work. I never meant to be a photographer. I’ve tried music, film, writing and finally this. It’s all about storytelling, and photographs are the shortest story of them all.”

Brevity is the soul of wit - when Shakespeare said it, he didn’t mean it for photographers. You’d hope he wouldn’t mind the context, after all, what could be more brief? That’s the case made by Kerry Wheeler (@kerrywheelerphoto), who wields a camera to slow the fogging of the past, and gaze at what might be.

“I’ve been around photography my entire life, my father shot for Time and National Geographic, I used to shadow him on family trips, learning without knowing it. He’s shot in over 100 countries, lived in dozens, he speaks eight languages and he’s been held hostage twice. We used to joke that he was a mix of Bond and the Dos Equis ‘most interesting man in the world’.

We spent a lot of time in the south of France, I always remember marvelling at the scenes. Stories were everywhere. My parents had very lavish friends, we lived a European riviera lifestyle and only now I look back and realise how lucky we were. Sometimes the Instagram culture that surrounds that place lacks soul. It’s a box ticking exercise, an acquisition of the scenery, few try to have a relationship with it. The imagery is stamped in my mind, memories I’ve sought to recreate from my childhood, all of my art is in homage to that time.

When the pandemic hit I moved in with my parents to take care of them. A weekend became a year. My father and I went through his archive, so much of it had never seen daylight, photos he didn’t think much of which I loved. Later this year we’ll launch Wheeler Collective, something he and I can contribute to under one banner. It’s a bit more Hemingway than Slim Aarons, telling the story of travels that span half a century. One day I’d like the Wheeler name to become synonymous with the great travel and lifestyle genre as we know it. I hope my father is around long enough to see that.”

Photos courtesy @kerrywheelerphoto and Wheeler Collective
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Built in the Mojave Desert to be “of the land”, this is the Hawk and Mesa retreat by Jeremy Levine (@hawkandmesa). 

The land in question is Pioneertown, a 19th century-style desert settlement built in 1946. With largely unpaved roads and sparse timber buildings, it feels a bit like a movie set, built for character to look older than it is.

Thankfully, the house we’re featuring is considerably more modern and is a lot more than a mere facade.

Shade is the operative feature - it’s essential out here. The oversized roof protects the house from the sun and will some day host an equally oversized solar array. Needless to say it’s energy usage will work out to be at least net zero then. The form of the house encourages what’s called the stack effect, where warm air from the outside is whisked upwards and out of strategically placed vents, encouraging airflow and passive cooling. Meanwhile all the wood in the house is reclaimed from local demolitions.

The timbers from a distance may fool the rest of Pioneertown into thinking the house fits in but let’s be clear, this isn’t a movie set. The practices at play here have moved on considerably since 1946 and much more so since the old west. Its aesthetic is classic, its functions are not.

Photos by @lance.gerber
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Major works of art deck the walls of @elfennmarrakech, starting with a collection of seven pieces “as a symbol of my belief in the project and the future stability of the country,” Vanessa Branson explains. It’s a project founded in the midst of a reinvention of the country; in the shadow of sweeping democratic reforms and a new royal, Morocco seemed like the perfect location to plant roots and to build something. “Howell [James, the co-founder of El Fenn] and I were looking for a small ‘two up two down’ riad as a little lock-up holiday home but once we entered El Fenn, then a dissolving ruin - but a magnificent dissolving ruin - there was no question that we had to buy it and we shook hands with the owner there and then.

The only problem was that it was easily ten times bigger than we realised. One thing led to another and before we knew it we had to open it up as a guest house, and then mission creep set in and the next riad along became available, and then the next, and then…”

The El Fenn team pored over the details, transforming this collection of rooms and annexes that were once uninhabitable to a luxe yet grounded trove of artisanal works. While some of the art on the walls is international, many of the pieces and details which make these spaces what they are came from local craftsmen who employed generations of knowledge into the spaces. “We only used natural materials - carved wood, leather floors, intricate Tadelakt plaster, zellige tiles.” Vanessa casually explains that “none of it was rocket science, but the eclectic mix was loved by our clients who felt part of the design rather than an imposition to it.”

Words by @nat_twiss for @type7
Photos courtesy @elfennmarrakech

node.text:
There’s something about the most unexpected discoveries that make the most satisfying stories. Marrakech, in the deserts just north of Africa’s Atlas Mountains, is a place full of the unexpected - Moorish and European influence meets West African culture, and maze-like souks and marketplaces feel plucked straight from antiquity in this true melting pot. Experiencing the city to its fullest requires a heavy dose of curiosity, and the riad-style hotel @elfennmarrakech is carving out a space just for those people, quickly developing a reputation as being the perfect launchpad to explore this underrated North African city.

You’d expect nothing less of a space created by Vanessa Branson, who has become something of an ambassador for the city and also founded the Marrakech Biennale; “I first visited Marrakech in 1982 and was instantly bowled over by the grace and dignity of the people here,” she explains. “We went on a road trip - it was then that I realised that the landscape reflected its people. For decades great artists have visited Marrakech - the mystery, the quality of the light, the sensuality are obvious magnets. There is a critical mass of creatives now, meaning that people are coming to live here for the other creatives they find here too.”

French designer Yves Saint Laurent might be the most famous recent inhabitant of the Ochre City, which he famously found influencing to his entire body of work, but even beyond him, there are countless musicians, perfumers, artists, and thinkers who have called the city their home.

“Playing a role in the cultural scene of the city is one of our core values,” Vanessa explains. “It not only enriches our own experience of working here, but our guests understand that by staying here that they are contributing to the local scene by simply staying here too. The Marrakech Biennale that ran for ten years from 2005 brought many an international artist to Marrakech - it had a massive impact in stimulating contemporary culture.”

Words by @nat_twiss for @type7
Photos courtesy @elfennmarrakech

node.text:
A feat of introspective architecture, this is Casa Sierra Fría by Esrawe (@esrawestudio). From the street view, slim brick facades and spot lighting enshrouds this Mexico City residence in mystery.

Inside, the central courtyard is alive with light, glass and greenery. A complete contrast to the exterior, the interior faces entirely in on itself, promoting an interaction between spaces that helps keep this family of four close to one another. It’s both private without coming across as defensive and communal without coming across as cramped. Perfectly balanced - as all things should be. 

Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7 
Photos by @cesarbejarstudio
